{
  "texts": [
    "For example, in writing a numeral in a long division problem, a student i) moves her hand in order to ii) move a pen in order to iii) leave certain marks on the page, and so on… in order to iv) record (i.e., to lay down a physical memory trace of) a step in her computation of the problem's solution.",
    "Descriptions (i) to (iv) seem to refer to different events; but in claiming that a movement (i) performed in order to record a stage of calculation (iv) are the same action, the A-D Principle propose a unity to these seemingly disparate elements as constituents of one and the same action.",
    "Since what connects the events is their co-participation in a rationally normatively and goal-directed sequence, we might think the cognitive properties of (iv) come to mark the unified action structured towards this end as an extended cognitive process.",
    "Indeed, this is, very roughly, what I'll suggest we should think if we adopt the Anscombean account.",
    "Sadly, things are rarely so simple."
  ]
}